ma-application-notes.para:
For example, it may be the case as described in the Interactions between entities (see Annex in CC Part 3) that the dependent component requires the base component to provide more security functionality in the composed TOE than included in the base component evaluation. This would be determined during the application of the and families. In this case the composition rationale evidence provided for would demonstrate that the assurance gained from the base component evaluation is unaffected. This may be achieved by means including:
Performing a re-evaluation of the base component focusing on the evidence relating to the extended part of the TSF;
Demonstrating that the extended part of the TSF cannot affect other portions of the TSF, and providing evidence that the extended part of the TSF provides the necessary security functionality.

